data.description:
Your task is to create a simple DOM structure, based on the one found in browsers. Create an instantiatible object, `DOM`, and give it the methods below.

> There are summaries below, but for more information on how these features work in the browser, check out the [MDN](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/Node) page.

> Note that while this spec is based on the way the browser's DOM works, not all methods are tested, and not all features are tested. The spec for a complete DOM is very extensive, and would take a long time to fully test and fully pass. These katas are intended to give you an idea of how different effects might be achieved, rather than build a feature-complete virtual DOM. Though if you're having fun making this, you can always carry on to add more features from the spec.

# .createElement(tag)
Returns a new HTML element node with the specified tag. Each node should have the features outlined below.

## node.tagName
The tag set at the time of the node's creation. Always uppercase.
*read-only*

```javascript
new DOM().createElement("div").tagName === "DIV";
// <div></div>
```

## node.parentNode
The node this is contained in. If there is no containing node, this will be `null`.
*read-only*

```javascript
// <div>
//    <span></span>
// </div>
span.parentNode === div
```

## node.appendChild(child)
Adds the specified child node into the node it's being appended to.

> NOTE: A node cannot be within two parent nodes at once. If a node is appended to a node other than the one it's already a child of, it should no longer be considered to be within that original parent node.

```javascript

// <header><strong></strong></header>
// <div>
//   <span></span>
// </div>
span.appendChild(strong);
// <header></header>
// <div>
//   <span></span>
//   <strong></strong>
// <div>
```

## node.childNodes
A special object that lets you see what's inside the node, without being able to affect it directly.

This is *not* an array, which would allow mutation of which child nodes are in the list. As such, it should not expose array-like methods that allow this to happen.

This is the equivalent of a "live nodelist" in the browser, but you only need to implement the following methods...

### .item(index)
Returns the child node at that index (the first child is at index 0).

```javascript
// <div>
//   <span></span>
//   <strong></strong>
//   <em></em>
// </div>
div.childNodes.item(1) === strong
```

### .length
How many child nodes are within this node.
*read-only*

```javascript
// <div><span></span><em></em></div>
div.childNodes.length === 2
```

## node.nextSibling
The node with the next lowest index that is within the same containing node. If there is none, this will be `null`.
*read-only*

## node.previousSibling
The node with the next highest index that is within the same containing node. If there is none, this will be `null`.
*read-only*

---

*This is part 1 of the HTML DOM series.* [Part 2 - Attributes](http://www.codewars.com/kata/5b3f207a6be5d8b2d20000b5)

### Author's Note
This is the first part of a series going over the HTML DOM and how it might be implemented programmatically. I am planning on creating more of these soon, but would appreciate feedback on the first installment so I can fix any stylistic problems in the way I put these together.
